Endpoints
Operation	Method	Path	Description
Create Item	POST	/items/	Add a new item with name and price.
Read Item	GET	/items/{item_id}	Retrieve an item by its ID.
Update Item	PUT	/items/{item_id}	Modify an existing itemâ€™s name and price.
Delete Item	DELETE	/items/{item_id}	Remove an item from the database.
Homepage	GET	/	Displays all items in a styled HTML table.
Request & Response Examples
Create Item
POST /items/

json
{
  "name": "Laptop",
  "price": 75000
}
Response:

json
{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "Laptop",
  "price": 75000
}
Read Item
GET /items/1

json
{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "Laptop",
  "price": 75000
}
Update Item
PUT /items/1

json
{
  "name": "Gaming Laptop",
  "price": 90000
}
Response:

json
{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "Gaming Laptop",
  "price": 90000
}
Delete Item
DELETE /items/1

json
{
  "message": "Item deleted successfully"
}
Homepage
GET /  
Displays all items in a styled HTML table:

html
<html>
  <body>
    <h1>Items in Database</h1>
    <table>
      <tr><th>ID</th><th>Name</th><th>Price</th></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>Laptop</td><td>75000</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td>Phone</td><td>30000</td></tr>
    </table>
  </body>
</html>
Benefits
Provides a foundation for real applications (inventory, user management, product catalogs).

Reusable structure: Extendable to multiple models (users, orders, categories).

Integration ready: Can be consumed by frontend apps (React, Angular, mobile).

Productionâ€‘ready: Deployable to cloud servers with minimal changes.
